class Solution {
public:

    /*
        The problem statement is bit confusing to understand. 
        First Let us Understand the question.
        If we assume the graph as a directed graph such that x->y means y is ritcher than x.

        Let's Take example of the question that has been provided to us in the question.
        richer = [[1,0],[2,1],[3,1],[3,7],[4,3],[5,3],[6,3]], quiet = [3,2,5,4,6,1,7,0]

        so its adjacency list representation would look something like

        0 | 1
        1 | 2 3
        2 |
        3 | 4 5 6
        4 | 
        5 | 
        6 | 
        7 | 3

        and now if we perform dfs over each node and store the minimum quietness and the candidate then we will get our answer.
        But this is not a efficient approach and may give TLE.

        So let's Try to look this question from some other perspective.

        What if we change the edge direction then our adjacency list will look something like this

        0 |  
        1 | 0
        2 | 1
        3 | 1 7
        4 | 3
        5 | 3
        6 | 3
        7 | 

        and in degree would be

        index - 0 1 2 3 4 5 6 7
        in    - 1 2 0 3 0 0 0 1

        and if we observe this the nodes with indegree 0 have the same queitness as they don't have any one richer than them.
        so here we may get an idea that we might use topological sort in this question to get our answer.

        so we will push the nodes with indegree 0 in the queue and keep their quetness as it is.
        as we perfom the topological sort we will check if the quiet[parent]<quiet[child], then this means that parent is richer than 
        child and he is more quieter than him then we can update our ans.
        and finally after performing topological sort we will get the answer.

    */

    vector<int> loudAndRich(vector<vector<int>>& richer, vector<int>& quiet) {
        int n=quiet.size();
        vector<vector<int> > graph(n);
        vector<int> in(n,0);
        for(auto i:richer)
        {
            graph[i[0]].push_back(i[1]);
            in[i[1]]++;
        }
        queue<int> q;
        vector<int> ans(n);
        iota(ans.begin(),ans.end(),0);
        for(int i=0;i<n;++i)
        {
            if(in[i]==0)
            {
                q.push(i);
                ans[i]=i;
            }
        }
        while(!q.empty())
        {
            int cur=q.front();
            q.pop();
            for(auto child:graph[cur])
            {
                in[child]--;
                if(quiet[cur]<quiet[child])
                {
                    quiet[child]=quiet[cur];
                    ans[child]=ans[cur];
                }
                if(in[child]==0)
                    q.push(child);
            }
        }
        return ans;
    }
};

From the richer array [[a,b]], create a map with key and adjacency list
* key = person index (b)
* adjacency list = list of people directly richer than person (push a into map.get(b))

Create answer array. From person 0 to person n - 1 (0 indexed), find the quietest person and fill it into answer array.
* getQuietest(person) method finds the quiestest person richer or equal to the given person. 
* It does so by comparing the quiet value of the given person and everyone in the person's adj list, and if the adjacent people have their own adj list, do a DFS search through it. This will cover all richer/equal to ppl. Find the min quiet value from all these people and return the index of the quietest person.
* Before every return value, store the return value into the memo map. This prevents searching through the same person again.

```
var loudAndRich = function(richer, quiet) {
    const map = new Map();
    for (const [rich, poor] of richer) {
        map.set(poor, (map.get(poor) || new Set()).add(rich));        
    }

    const memo = new Map();
    const getQuietest = (person) => {
        if (memo.has(person)) return memo.get(person);
        const richerList = map.get(person);
        let min = quiet[person];
        let quietest = person;
        if (!richerList) {
            memo.set(person, quietest);
            return quietest;
        }
        for (const rich of richerList) {         
            if (quiet[getQuietest(rich)] < min) {
                min = quiet[getQuietest(rich)];
                quietest = getQuietest(rich);
            }            
        }
        memo.set(person, quietest);
        return quietest;
    }
    const answer = [];
    for (let i=0; i<quiet.length; i++) {
        answer.push(getQuietest(i));
    }
    return answer;
};
