# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
Right after looking the problem I knew that this was about DFS as we have to iterate all the nodes(people) which have more money. So, first of all ,I have created a graph where edges will be directed from poor person to rich which enables us to reach nodes which are only richer than the current one. I have used memoization to store node values which have least quiet value and more money that current node to avoid overlapping subproblems. 

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
Create a graph (adjacency list) in which edges will be directed from poor person to richer. Then for each node traverse to richer nodes(i.e adjacent nodes) and find the node which has least quiet value in traversal. Store the node value instead of quieteness value as we ultimately need nodes.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
Implementation is just as normal DFS, so time complexity is O(V+E) where V is number of vertices and E is number of edges.


- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
O(V) for one dimensional dp vector and O(E) for recursion stack space as DFS will be called E number of times. So overall space complexity is O(V+E).

