solutions.content:
I figured this is not the "right" solution, doesn't work for (16,17) although it works for this leetcode question.

The basic idea is for all the squares with sides from 1 to width (inclusive), try to place it at a point in rectangle's top left corner located at (i, j) where i + side <= length and j + side <= width. From placing this square at (i, j), we can cut the rectangle into 4 smaller rectangles. Then, we do the similar computation recursively. Use an array to store the calculated width and length to avoid repeated calculation.

Some special cases to consider:
1. the rectangle's width or length is 0, this is not a rectangle, it's just a line, thus, return 0
2. if the reactangle's width equals length, this is a square, return 1
3. if the rectangle's length is multiple of it's width, then the min squares to form the rectangle is it's length/wdith

```
class Solution {
    int[][] cache = new int[14][14];
    public int tilingRectangle(int n, int m) {
        return dfs(new int[]{n, m});
    }
    int dfs(int[] rect) {
        if (rect[0] == 0 || rect[1] == 0) return 0;
        int width = Math.min(rect[0], rect[1]);
        int length = Math.max(rect[0], rect[1]);
        if (length % width == 0) return length / width;
        if (cache[width][length] != 0) return cache[width][length];
        int res = Integer.MAX_VALUE;
        for(int s = 1; s <= width; s++) {
            for(int i = 0; i <= length - s; i++) {
                for(int j = 0; j <= width - s; j++) {
                    int c1 = dfs(new int[]{i + s, j});
                    int c2 = dfs(new int[]{length - i - s, j + s});
                    int c3 = dfs(new int[]{length - i, width - j - s});
                    int c4 = dfs(new int[]{i, width - j});

                    res = Math.min(res, c1 + c2 + c3 + c4 + 1);
                }
            }
        }
        cache[width][length] = res;
        return res;
    }
}
```

