# Intuition

I found this exercise interesting because I am so used to implement dynamic programming that I didnt even consider using pruning on the Backtrack solution.

Here I will share both and their times so you can see that its not always that DP wins.

The problem arises by the fact that we have a lot of DP states (too many) as it is often the case in backtrack problems. The thing is that you should not forget another powerful (but less common) alternative: pruning.

Specially if you are searching for min max solution pruning may be a viable alternative. The idea is:
- When you are navigating down the backtrack check the partial result against the current global result, if the result is already unsatisfactory and it's only going to get worst, why continue? stop/prune/discard the current navigation.

Curiosity: Some powerful algorithms such as `Alpha-Beta Prune` use exactly this idea and.

# Approach
- Dynamic Programming
- Backtrack Pruning

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
  - Dynamic Programming: $$O(m*n^m)$$
  - Backtrack Pruning: ?

- Space complexity:
  - Dynamic Programming: $$O(m*n^m)$$
  - Backtrack Pruning: $$O(m*n^m)$$ <- The stack

# Code

## Dynamic Programming
![image.png](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/329cf626-af6f-4339-87d6-287df68328d5_1680541703.18383.png)

```java
class Solution {
    public int tilingRectangle(int n, int m) {
        if(m==n) return 1;
        return helper(n,new int[m],n*m,new HashMap<>());
    }
    int helper(int rowHeight, int[] col, int free, Map<Integer,Integer> memo) {
        if(free==0) return 0;
        int key=0, pow=1;
        for(int i=0;i<col.length;i++,pow*=rowHeight) key+=pow*col[i];
        if(memo.containsKey(key)) return memo.get(key);
        int sc=0;
        for(int i=1;i<col.length;i++)
            if(col[i]<col[sc]) sc=i;
        int baseHeight=col[sc];
        int end=1;
        while(sc+end<col.length&&
            col[sc+end]==col[sc]) end++;
        int min=Integer.MAX_VALUE;
        end=Math.min(end,rowHeight-baseHeight);
        for(int i=0;i<end;i++)
            col[sc+i]+=end;
        for(int k=end-1;k>-1;k--) {
            min=Math.min(min,helper(rowHeight,col,free-(k+1)*(k+1),memo));
            if(min==0) {
                for(int i=0;i<=k;i++) col[sc+i]-=k+1;
                break;
            }
            for(int i=0;i<=k;i++) col[sc+i]-=1;
            col[sc+k]-=k;
        }
        memo.put(key,min+1);
        return min+1;
    }
}
```

## Backtracking with Prune
![image.png](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/4f701cfa-21cb-41f5-ac68-d887c69b40a2_1680541644.8433423.png)

```java
class Solution {
    int min;
    public int tilingRectangle(int n, int m) {
        if(m==n) return 1;
        min=m*n;
        helper(n,new int[m],n*m,0);
        return min;
    }
    void helper(int rowHeight, int[] col, int free, int count) {
        if(free==0) {
            min=Math.min(min,count);
            return;
        }
        if(count>min) return;
        int sc=0;
        for(int i=1;i<col.length;i++)
            if(col[i]<col[sc]) sc=i;
        int baseHeight=col[sc];
        int end=1;
        while(sc+end<col.length&&end<rowHeight-baseHeight&&
            col[sc+end]==col[sc]) end++;
        for(int i=0;i<end;i++)
            col[sc+i]+=end;
        for(int k=end-1;k>-1;k--) {
            helper(rowHeight,col,free-(k+1)*(k+1),count+1);
            for(int i=0;i<=k;i++) col[sc+i]-=1;
            col[sc+k]-=k;
        }
    }
}
