| **8**    |       |       |       |       |       |       | 1     |       | 2     |        |        |        |         |
| **9**    |       |       |       |       |       |       |       | 2     |       | 4      |        |        |         |
| **10**   |       |       |       |       |       |       |       |       | 4     |        | 5      | 1      |         |
| **11**   |       |       |       |       | 1     | 1     |       |       |       | 5      |        | 5      | 2       |
| **12**   |       |       |       |       |       |       |       |       |       | 1      | 5      |        | 6       |
| **13**   |       |       |       |       |       | 2     | 2     |       |       |        | 2      | 6      |         |

I guess we could account for these errors, with additional *Boundary Condition* code. 

A better approach is to check all the combinations, while remembering the sub-solutions:
```
public class Solution
{
    private readonly Dictionary<(int, int), int> _dict = new();

    public int TilingRectangle(int n, int m)
    {
        if (n > m) (n, m) = (m, n);
        if (n == 0) return 0;
        if (n == 1) return m;
        if (n == m) return 1;
        if (m % n == 0) return m / n;
        if (_dict.TryGetValue((n, m), out var answer)) return answer;
        if (m > 2 * n)
        {
            var squares = m / n - 1;
            var leftover = m - squares * n;
            return _dict[(n, m)] = squares + TilingRectangle(n, leftover);
        }

        var min = 1 + TilingRectangle(m - n, n);
        for (var i = (m + 1) / 2; i < n; i++)
        for (var j = 0; j <= m - i; j++)
        {
            var sum = 2
                      + TilingRectangle(n - i, i + j)
                      + TilingRectangle(m - i - j, i - m + n)
                      + TilingRectangle(j, 2 * i - m);
            min = Math.Min(min, sum);
        }

        return _dict[(n, m)] = min;
    }
}
```

This algorithm performs the following steps:
1. If `(n > m)`, look for the mirrored solution at `(m, n)`. That way `n` is always less than `m`.
1. Check the trivial solutions.
1. Check the cache for a previous solution.
1. For long rectangles, chop off squares and count the remaining rectangle.
1. Or look for the minimum out of the following:
  a. One big square (the heigth of the rectangle) and the remaining rectangle.
  b. Check all combinations of two smaller squares (combined to be the width of the rectangle), and their remaining three rectangles.

