# Approach
- 
  No need of priority Queue.
  Just few time back I post brief explanation. I deleted that, After relasing there are tons of explanation available. Let me just show you my solution where I have not used PQ using circular dependency trick.
- Look at the problem in a different way. Say we have all even numbers we can devide them by 2 until it becomes odd.
- Rest of everything similar to what it is explained in other blogs/solutions.

**is circular dependency always available ?**
No ! to achieve circular dependency of adjacent maximum minimum. You would have to make all number close to maximum or minimum.

```
for (int i = n - 1 ; i>= 0; i--) {
        while (a[i] % 2 == 0 and a[i]/2 >= mn) a[i] >>= 1;
}
```
<h2>Why Not Priority Queue ?</h4>

priority queue is good when we have randomness in ordering.
Let me give an example.

X = [16, 18, 44 80]
here I as I mentioned before. We would assume we can only have even and we  can keep reducing untill becomes odd.
so for X array maximum value if 80 right ?
If we devide by 2 for 80, it would be 40, but you see you can further reduce this and to 20 right ? then to 10 ?
And also for the current scenario our minimum 16.
So with all other numbers we would try to reach 16 as close as possible but will not cross it. By crossing I meant the reduced value should not be < 16.

so after approaching 16. Array X looks like - [16, 18, 22, 20]
Now lets sort it  - [16, 18, 20, 22]
now you see this particular array is arraged such a way that even the biggest number in the array (i.e 22) if it is devided by 2 then it would be lesser than 16.
so [16, 18, 20, 22] - lets halve last (3rd) index.
