solutions.content:
Intuition behind this is tricky at first.
1. We can only multiply a odd number once because after that it becomes even.
2. We can divide a even number multiple times until it becomes odd.
3. There is one issue of doing the same operation again and again, for eg: we have 10, we divided it by 2 , and then again in the next step we multiplied it by 2. It's not required. For that reason we will use a MAX Priority Queue. (You can also use min priority queue).

Steps:
1. Change all the odd elements in the array to even. As multiplication can only be done once, we will not use multiplication further after this step. This solves the issue of repeating.
2. Add all the elements into the Queue. Store the min value of the array in a variable.
3. Now we have a priority queue with max value which is even at the top.
4. we will run a loop until the max value becomes odd by dividing the max value by 2. Parallelly we will update our diff of max and min. You can understand the loop by looking at the code. 
5. Finally we will return the min between the diff and queues max-min.

Look through the code. It'll be easier if you dry run this.
```
class Solution {
    public int minimumDeviation(int[] nums) {

        PriorityQueue<Integer> pq = new PriorityQueue<>(Collections.reverseOrder());
        int min = Integer.MAX_VALUE;

        for(int i : nums){
            if(i % 2 == 1) i *= 2;

            pq.add(i);
            min = Math.min(min, i);
        }
        int diff = Integer.MAX_VALUE;

        while(pq.peek() % 2 == 0){
            int max = pq.remove();
            diff = Math.min(diff, max - min);

            max /= 2;
            min = Math.min(min, max);
            pq.add(max);
        }
        return Math.min(diff, pq.peek() - min);
    }
}

```

