# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
1. We can start by making all odd elements even by multiplying them with 
2. Then, we can try to divide the maximum element by 2 as many times as possible to minimize the deviation.
3. After each division, we need to keep track of the minimum deviation we have seen so far.
4. Repeat step 2 and 3 until we can no longer divide the maximum element by 2.

- # Algorithm
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
1. Multiply all odd elements by 2 and add them to a priority queue
2. Initialize the minimum deviation to be the difference between the maximum element and the top element of the priority queue.
3. Repeat the following until the maximum element is even:
    - Remove the maximum element from the priority queue.
    - Divide it by 2 and add it to the priority queue.
    - Update the minimum deviation if the difference between the maximum element and the top element of the priority queue is smaller than the current minimum deviation.
4. Return the minimum deviation.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
    - The multiplication of odd numbers takes O(n) time.
    - The priority queue operations take O(log n) time each.
    - We can divide the maximum element by 2 at most log(maximum element) times.
    - Therefore, the overall time complexity is O(n log n log(maximum element)).

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
    - We need to store all odd elements in the priority queue, which takes O(n) space.
