**NOTE :**
* If the element is even, divide it by 2.
* If the element is odd, multiply it by 2.
* Also ![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/5354c083-4e18-4544-bd17-41449fe5fb15_1645247965.4044886.png)

**IDEA :**
1. So for the first time if we multiply it by 2 then all odd become even and no odd numbers will be there in the array. (Main motive to do so that we need not to multipy further array elements, and can get the min element from that).
1. Find min element **'mi'** from the array.
1. Now find the max element 'ma' from the array and store the diff 'd' among **ma - mi**(max-min).
1. Repeat step 2 until the max becomes odd (so we can not divide it further on).
1. Also, we have to check whether the **ma/2** is not less than **mi**, if it is so then mi = ma/2.

**IF WE LINEARLY FIND MAX FOR ALL THE TIME THEN IT WILL GIVE TLE**
So we have to use concept like **PRIORITY QUEUE**, the idea is of **MAX-HEAP** (the topmost element is the largest element among all, and the leaf element has the smallest element).

**CODE : **
```
int minimumDeviation(vector<int>& a)
    {
        int n=a.size();
        priority_queue<int> pq;
		// changing odd to even and also storing to the priority_queue.
        for(int i=0; i<n; i++)
        {
            if(a[i]%2!=0)
                a[i]*=2;
            pq.push(a[i]);
        }
		// finding minimum element 
        int mi=*min_element(a.begin(), a.end());
        int d = INT_MAX;

		//always find max untill max/2!=0
        while(pq.top()%2==0)
        {
			// removing the max element from the priority queue and finding the diff.
            int ma = pq.top();
            pq.pop();
            d = min(d, ma - mi);
			//updating the minimum.
            mi = min(mi, ma/2);
			//pushing max/2 to the MAX-HEAP.
            pq.push(ma/2);

        }
        return min(d, pq.top() - mi);
    }

