# Approach
1. Make all odd numbers even by multiplying them by 2.
2. Add all numbers to a priority queue (max heap).
3. Keep track of the minimum value in the array (mi) as elements are added to the priority queue.
4. Repeatedly perform the following steps until an odd element is encountered:
    - Remove the maximum element (num) from the priority queue.
    - Calculate the new deviation as the difference between the maximum element and the minimum element (mi).
    - Update the minimum deviation if the new deviation is less than the current deviation.
    - If the maximum element is even, divide it by 2 and add it back to the priority queue.
    - Update the minimum element (mi) if necessary.
5. The final deviation is the minimum deviation that the array can have after performing some number of operations.
# Complexity
- Time complexity:
O(n*logn)

- Space complexity:
O(n)

# Code
```java []
class Solution {
    public int minimumDeviation(int[] nums) {
        int mi = Integer.MAX_VALUE, res = Integer.MAX_VALUE;
        PriorityQueue<Integer> pq = new PriorityQueue<>((a,b)->b-a);
        for(int num: nums){
            if(num % 2 == 1)    num *= 2;
            pq.add(num);
            mi = Math.min(mi,num);
        }
        while(true){
            int num = pq.poll();
            res = Math.min(res, num - mi);
            if(num % 2 == 1) break;
            mi = Math.min(mi,num/2);
            pq.add(num/2);
        }
        return res;
    }
}
```

