solutions.content:
The first thing to realize is that you can safely double every odd without changing the answer. This is because you can always just half them later. This reduces the problem to just halfing even numbers.

For example inputs of [16, 5, 3, 4], and [16, 10, 6, 4] will give the same answer guaranteed.

This new array has a max and a min. Let's try to reduce the max as much as possible without reducing the min. To do this, let's keep halfing every even number without ever reducing a number below that minimum

For example [16, 10, 6, 4] is reduced [4, 5, 6, 4]. **A candidate solution is 6 - 4 = 2**.

We may not be done yet. We reduced the max as much as possible in the previous step. Let's reduce the min *as little as possible* in the next step. We can achieve this by halving the largest number(s).

In this case [4, 5, 6, 4] is reduced to [4, 5, 3, 4].

Now we repeat the previous step.

Its impossible to reduce the max without also reducing the min so [4, 5, 3, 4] remains [4, 5, 3, 4].

**Another candidate solution is 5 - 3 = 2.**

Now we attempt to reduce the min but the largest number is an odd number so there is no point in reducing the array further; it can only make things worse. We are done.

The final solution is the minimum of the candidates. min(2, 2) = **2**;

For N integers of size K, we at most half the N integers log(K) times. Since K is bounded to a 32bit integer. The **final time complexity is O(N)**. And we did the calculation with the original array so **O(1) extra memory**.

Code:
```
var minimumDeviation = function(nums) {

    // Double all odd number so that all numbers are even.
    // After this, we can focus on halfing numbers until we
    // find the optimal solution
    for (let i = 0; i < nums.length; i++) {
        if (nums[i] % 2 === 1) {
            nums[i] *= 2
        }
    }

    let best = Infinity;
    let done = false
    while (!done) {
        // Reduce the array such that all the values are as close as possible
        // to the minimum value. This will become a candidate solution
        const min = Math.min(...nums);
        for (let i = 0; i < nums.length; i++) {
            while (nums[i] % 2 === 0 && nums[i] / 2 >= min) {
                nums[i] /= 2;
            }
        }

        // Now let's reduce the array by the smallest amount possible
        // This is achieved halving the largest number
        const max = Math.max(...nums);
        best = Math.min(best, max - min);
        done = true;
        for (let i = 0; i < nums.length; i++) {
            if (nums[i] === max && nums[i] % 2 === 0) {
                // if this code block is never hit, it means the maximum is odd 
                // and we can no longer reduce the array; we are done.
                done = false;
                nums[i] /= 2;
            }    
        }
    }
    return best;
};
```

