# Intuition
Key phrase is "minimum of maximum".  Almost any time you see these two words together in a problem statement, some form of binary search can be used.  In this case, we use ternary search.

# Approach
The immediate thought that came to my head was that this must be a binary search type problem.  The general idea is that we are trying to "reach" some number (our mid) and we want all numbers to get as close as possible to that number.  

After coding it out a bit, I realized I didn't have anything to compare to know whether I should search left or right on my next iteration.  After some additional thought, I realized that use ternary search and compare in which side of the search we get a better result and continue our search there.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
O(nlogn)

- Space complexity:
O(1) or O(N) if you count the input

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int getCount(int tar, vector<int>& nums){
        int lo = INT_MAX;
        int hi = INT_MIN;
        for(int i = 0;i<nums.size();i++){
            int cur = nums[i];
            if(cur%2==1){
                if(abs(tar-(cur*2))<abs(tar-(cur))){
                    cur*=2;
                }
            }
            else{
                while(cur%2==0&&abs(tar-(cur/2))<abs(tar-(cur))){
                    cur/=2;
                }
            }
            hi = max(hi,cur);
            lo = min(lo,cur);
        }
        return hi-lo;
    }
    int minimumDeviation(vector<int>& nums) {
        sort(nums.begin(),nums.end());
        int l = 0;
        int r = nums[nums.size()-1];
        int mid1 = l + (r-l)/3;
        int mid2 = r - (r-l)/3; 
        int mi = INT_MAX;
        while(l<=r){
            mid1 = l + (r-l)/3;
            mid2 = r - (r-l)/3; 
            int c1 = getCount(mid1,nums);
            int c2 = getCount(mid2,nums);
            mi = min({mi,c1,c2});
            if(c1<c2){
                r = mid2-1;
            }
            else{
                l = mid1+1;
            }
        }
        return mi;
    }
};
```

