# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
solve this problem, we need to perform the following steps:

Multiply all odd numbers by 2 so that we can perform only even divisions later.

Create a max-heap of the modified array.

While the maximum element of the heap is even, we can divide it by 2 and replace the maximum element with the result.

Keep track of the minimum deviation during the above process.

Return the minimum deviation as the final answer.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
Time complexity: O(n log n), where n is the size of the input array. We perform n operations of adding and removing elements from a priority queue, each of which takes log n time.

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

Space complexity: O(n), where n is the size of the input array. We need to store all elements of the input array in the priority queue.

please upvote if you find the soultion helpful.
# Code
```
import java.util.*;

class Solution {
    public int minimumDeviation(int[] nums) {
        PriorityQueue<Integer> pq = new PriorityQueue<>(Collections.reverseOrder());
        int minDeviation = Integer.MAX_VALUE;
        int minNum = Integer.MAX_VALUE;

        // Multiply all odd numbers by 2 and add to heap
        for (int num : nums) {
            if (num % 2 == 1) {
                num *= 2;
            }
            pq.add(num);
            minNum = Math.min(minNum, num);
        }

        // Keep dividing maximum element by 2 until it becomes odd
        while (true) {
            int maxNum = pq.poll();
            minDeviation = Math.min(minDeviation, maxNum - minNum);

            if (maxNum % 2 == 1) {
                break;
            }
            maxNum /= 2;
            pq.add(maxNum);
            minNum = Math.min(minNum, maxNum);
        }

        return minDeviation;
    }
}

```

